        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The velocity resolution 0.1 km/sec and velocity coverage 80km/sec are enough to study the Keplerian disk around our target source in detail.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The main science goal of this proposal is to see the innermost Keplerian disk.  So we choose the maximum achievalbe resolution at Band 6.  The linear scaes at a distance of our target source, 429 pc of angular resolutions 37 and 500 mas are 15 AU and 215 AU, respectively.  

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Line: C18O (2-1)
We found a C18O (3-2) line toward our target source from the JCMT archive.  The peak antenna temperature of this line is around 2K (Figure 3 in the proposal).  We assume that antenna temperature of C18O (3-2) is same as that of C18O (2-1).  The flux in units of Jy is 52Jy assuming that the aperature efficiency of the 15m JCMT is 0.6.  We also assume that the effective size of a disk around our target source at a distance 429 pc is 300 AU.  The angular size of the disk is 0.7 arcsec.  Our synthesized beam is 0.037 arcsec.  So the peak line flux density per beam is 52 Jyx(0.037/0.7)^2= 144mJy, assuming a uniform density distribution of the disk. We can detect the C18O(3-2) line with a S/N=24.  We will smooth the spectra to get a higher S/N if necessary.  

Line: 13CO(2-1)
Since the detected peak antenna temperature of 13CO (3-2) is 2.4 K (see Figure 3), which is larger than 2.0 K of C18O (3-2), we expect to detect 13CO (2-1) line with a S/N larger than S/N=24 for the case of C18O (2-1).

Continuum: The 450um and 850um peak fluxes of SCUBA 2 around our target source are 997 mJy and 268 mJy, respectively.  Based on the peak fluxes, we found a spectral index of -2.0.  The estimated peak flux at 1.3mm using the spectral index of -2 is 115 mJy.  Again we assue the size of disk, 300pc, the peak continuum flux density per beam is 115mJy/(0.037/0.7)^2=0.29mJy.  We can detect the continuum with a S/N=14.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
