    <prp:abstract>Many pre-ALMA interferometric observations have found Keplerian disks around Class 0, 1 and 2 sources.  Because of their limited resolution, they however probed disks in the distance range of from 100 AU to 1000 AU.  At the outskirt of a disk, there is infalling material, which will be eventually converted into rotating disk material as it approaches to a central source.  It is therefore more likely to see the Keplerian motion in the inner part of disks.  We propose to observe a Class I source in the Serpens molecular cloud with the longest baseline at Band 6, which will resolve the linear scale of 15 AU at the distance of our target source.  We found the Keplerian inner disk (&lt;1 AU) in this target with high-resolution infrared spectroscopic observations.  Our ALMA observations will provide a bona fide innermost Keplerian disk.
</prp:abstract>
